<div id="main_content">
	<h2>UCF President Hitt Receives Legacy Award from Orlando Business Journal</h2>
	
	<p class="article_info">
		
			By Tom Evelyn
		
		<span class="date">Oct. 18, 2006</span></p>
	
	
	
		<div class="article_img" style="width: 196px;">

			<img alt="Article Main Picture" src="../resources/sites/UCF/content/live/NEWS/0/NE678/en_US/hittcrop.jpg" height="261" width="196"  /> 
			
				<p class="photo_credit">Photo: UCF File</p>
			
			<p>John Hitt became the fourth president of UCF in 1992. During his tenure, enrollment has more than doubled, research funding has more than tripled and the number of doctorates awarded each year has more than quadrupled.</p>
			
				<p class="note"><a class="full_photo" id="popup.jsp?article_id=0024004105bd60439010c0c76ce2f005078">Full Photo</a></p>
			
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
					
						
						
						
					
			
			
			
		</div>
	
	
	
	
	
	
	
		
			<div id="related">
				<h3>Related Contacts and Links:</h3>
				<ul>
		
		<li>
		
			
				<h4><a href="mailto:tevelyn@mail.ucf.edu">Tom Evelyn</a></h4>
			
			
			
				<ul>
				<li>407-823-5988</li>
			
			</ul>
		
		</li>
	
	
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.president.ucf.edu/">Office of the President</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
		
		<li>
		
			<h4><a href="http://www.med.ucf.edu/">Health Sciences Campus (College of Medicine)</a></h4>
		
		</li>
	
	
	 </ul></div> 
	
	
			
	
	
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	
		
	
	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>
<placetype></placetype>
University of
<placename></placename>
Central Florida President John Hitt was honored with the Orlando Business Journal's Most Influential Businessmen Legacy Award on Tuesday for his work to bring a medical school to <city></city>Orlando and the impact his 14-year presidency has had on
<place></place>
Central Florida's growth and prosperity.</p>
<p>&quot;John Hitt has transformed the
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
University of
<placename></placename>
Central Florida into a world-class institution whose success and impact in this community have been undeniable,&quot; said Orlando Business Journal Publisher Ann Sonntag as she introduced the inaugural award. It was presented during the newspaper's annual Most Influential Businessmen awards ceremony.</p>
<p>Tavistock Group CEO Sesh Thakkar, whose company donated $12.5 million and 50 acres at
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
Lake
<placename></placename>
Nona for the UCF College of Medicine, was named the Most Influential Businessmen Man of the Year for his support of the college and efforts to bring the Burnham Institute to
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
Lake
<placename></placename>
Nona.</p>
<p>During the ceremony Tuesday night, Hitt talked about being among the first in his family to get a college degree and the difference that made in his life.</p>
<p>&quot;I know very personally what it means to have that opportunity,&quot; Hitt said. &quot;When we do our jobs well, we enable people to transform their lives.&quot;</p>
<p>Hitt became the fourth president of UCF in 1992. During his tenure, enrollment has more than doubled, research funding has more than tripled and the number of doctorates awarded each year has more than quadrupled.</p>
<p>In line with his goal for UCF to be <country-region></country-region>
<place></place>
America's leading partnership university, Hitt joined former
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
University of
<placename></placename>
South Florida President Betty Castor in 1996 to create the Florida High Tech Corridor Council to attract, retain and expand high-tech industry from the
<place></place>
<placename></placename>
Space
<placetype></placetype>
Coast to
<place></place>
<placename></placename>
Tampa
<placetype></placetype>
Bay.</p>
<p>More recently he oversaw the establishment of the
<placename></placename>
Florida
<placename></placename>
Interactive
<placename></placename>
Entertainment
<placetype></placetype>
Academy in downtown <city></city>
<place></place>
Orlando and the new Rosen College of Hospitality Management campus near International Drive. He also led the effort to build an on-campus football stadium that will open next year.</p>
<p>This&nbsp;year he secured approval from the Florida Board of Governors to establish a
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
College of
<placename></placename>
Medicine for which he helped to raise more than $100 million in donations and matching funds. The college will train much-needed doctors and provide billions of dollars of local economic benefit from a cluster of medical businesses and research companies expected to move to the UCF Health Sciences Campus at
<place></place>
<placetype></placetype>
Lake
<placename></placename>
Nona.</p>
<p>&quot;Today, the
<placetype></placetype>
University of
<placename></placename>
Central Florida is one of largest universities in the country,&quot; said Most Influential Businessmen co-presenter Ed Baxa, managing partner of the <city></city>
<place></place>
Orlando office of the law firm Foley &amp; Lardner LLP. &quot;Its impact here in
<place></place>
Central Florida is even greater. And we have John Hitt to thank for that.&quot;</p>
<p>Earlier this year, Orlando Magazine named Hitt the most powerful person in
<place></place>
Central Florida in its &quot;Power 50&quot; list. In January, the Orlando Sentinel selected him as the Central Floridian of the Year.</p>
		
	
	<p id="back"><a href="index?page=news">&lt; Back to the Newsroom</a></p>

